---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import AboutBlock from '../components/AboutBlock.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Raven Roberts"
  description="Background, research direction, and the longer arc of Tardigrade Innovation."
>
  <Section
    id="about"
    index="§ 04 — ORIGIN"
    title="The {accent}."
    titleAccent="operator"
    blurb="Tardigrade Innovation is a one-person research lab in Newport, Tennessee — for now. The longer arc is to build a multi-modal physics institution in East Tennessee that protects the land and employs locally."
  >
    <AboutBlock />

    <div class="long-form">
      <h2>Background</h2>
      <p>
        I started building computers and writing code with my father at age eight.
        Began dual enrollment at thirteen, completing two associate degrees from
        St. Petersburg College with a 3.89 GPA before moving to concurrent
        enrollment at Harvard Extension School and Roane State Community College
        — 4.0 GPAs at both.
      </p>
      <p>
        Professional career started with two internships at Crayon — first remotely
        from the US, then in person in Vienna for the summer of 2023. The Vienna
        placement also gave me conversational German, adding to my existing English
        and Russian. After Crayon, I joined Flomoney in Singapore as their founding
        AI and robotics engineer, where I shipped a legal RAG chatbot, a humanoid
        autonomous robot stack, and a sign language translation system across one
        focused year.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tardigrade Innovation LLC was founded in fall 2024 to give the work a proper
        institutional home — a recognized entity for collaborative research, a
        holder of patents, and the eventual seed of something larger.
      </p>

      <h2>Research direction</h2>
      <p>
        The active research threads include a variational quantum classifier for
        LIGO gravitational-wave signals (collaborative work with a UCSB PhD candidate,
        running on real IBM Quantum hardware, with an arXiv preprint in preparation),
        a Clifford geometric algebra neural architecture with rotation and Lorentz
        equivariance native to the representation, and exploratory work on lattice
        gauge theory surrogates and amplituhedron geometry.
      </p>
      <p>
        Alongside the computational work, I build the instruments. The lab in Newport
        currently has seven active rigs in various states of operation, from an MPCVD
        reactor for NV-center diamond growth to a 4-meter L-band radio interferometer
        used for 21-cm hydrogen line observations and Crab Pulsar timing.
      </p>

      <h2>The Appalachian mission</h2>
      <p>
        The longer arc of my work is to build a multi-modal research institution
        in East Tennessee — a privately founded laboratory that combines radio
        astronomy, gravitational-wave instrumentation, and quantum materials science,
        anchored to the land by intention rather than federal committee.
        Green Bank, West Virginia, is the closest existing analog: a research site
        whose presence has shaped land use, limited cell towers, and kept a particular
        kind of quiet alive in the Potomac Highlands.
      </p>
      <p>
        The mission has both scientific and political dimensions. A serious research
        site in East Tennessee creates jobs that require real skills and can be
        learned locally — welding, RF engineering, machining, software — without
        requiring the people who fill them to leave the region. It also functions
        as a kind of structural protection against the development pressure that's
        been hollowing out Appalachia for a generation. A 500-acre radio quiet zone
        with an active research institution on it cannot be rezoned for condominiums.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am Appalachian by birth, and the long-term goal of my physics education
        is to come back with the credentials and the tools to build something
        permanent. The physics degree, the LIGO connections, the national lab
        relationships — those are not an exit from Appalachia. They are the inputs
        to a return.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .long-form {
    margin-top: 4rem;
    max-width: 64ch;
    font-family: var(--display);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--bone);
    font-weight: 300;
  }
  .long-form h2 {
    font-family: var(--display);
    font-style: italic;
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 1.6rem;
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
    color: var(--bone);
  }
  .long-form p + p { margin-top: 1.2em; }
  .long-form strong { color: var(--phosphor); font-weight: 400; }
</style>
